│ ### 1. Understanding the Issue ###                                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `slp-vectorizer` is crashing with an assertion failure, `Assertion valid() &&          │
│ "InstructionsState is invalid."' failed`, within the `InstructionsState::getMainOp()`      │
│ method. This indicates that `getMainOp()` is being called on an `InstructionsState` object │
│ that has not been properly initialized.                                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ The backtrace reveals the crash occurs during the cost analysis of a potential             │
│ vectorization candidate, specifically when checking for a "gather-shuffled" pattern        │
│ (`isGatherShuffledEntry`). This check involves inspecting a `TreeEntry` that represents a  │
│ group of scalar instructions. The `TreeEntry` contains an `InstructionsState` member       │
│ (`S`), which holds information about the instructions, including the "main" operation. The │
│ assertion fails because this `InstructionsState` is invalid when `getMainOp()` is called   │
│ on it.                                                                                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log ###                                                           │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `opt` log provides crucial clues:                                                      │
│ - The vectorizer identifies a horizontal reduction involving a chain of `xor` operations.  │
│ - It starts building a "vectorization tree" and creates several `TreeEntry` nodes.         │
│ - The log shows the creation of three `TreeEntry` nodes for `load` instructions.           │
│ - The third `TreeEntry` created, for scalars `%7` and `%3`, is printed with                │
│ `UserTreeIndex: <invalid>`.                                                                │
│ - Immediately after, the log shows `SLP: Calculating cost for tree of size 4`, and then    │
│ the crash occurs.                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The invalid `UserTreeIndex` for the third `TreeEntry` is a strong indicator of the         │
│ problem. A `TreeEntry` represents a node in the vectorization tree. Its `UserTreeIndex`    │
│ should point to the `TreeEntry` that uses its result. An invalid index suggests this node  │
│ is disconnected from the main tree structure being built.                                  │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis ###                                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ The core issue lies in how `BoUpSLP::buildTree` constructs the vectorization tree. When it │
│ encounters a set of scalar values, it creates a `TreeEntry` for them. If these scalars are │
│ operands to another instruction that is also being vectorized, the new `TreeEntry`'s       │
│ `UserTreeIndex` is set to point to the user `TreeEntry`.                                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ In this specific case, the horizontal reduction logic (`HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce`) │
│ initiates tree construction. It gathers all the operands of the reduction chain (`%0`,     │
│ `%1`, ..., `%7`). It then calls `BoUpSLP::buildTree` on these operands.                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ The problem is that `buildTree` does not create a root `TreeEntry` for the initial set of  │
│ scalars passed to it. Instead, it iterates through them, finds their users, and builds     │
│ sub-trees for those. If some of the initial scalars are not used by any common instruction │
│ that can be vectorized (i.e., they don't form a sub-problem that `buildTree` can handle),  │
│ the `TreeEntry` created for them will not have a user within the tree being constructed.   │
│ Consequently, its `UserTreeIndex` remains in its default invalid state.                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ Later, during cost analysis (`getTreeCost`), the vectorizer iterates through all           │
│ `TreeEntry` nodes, including the disconnected one. When `getEntryCost` is called on this   │
│ node, it proceeds down a path that eventually calls `getMainOp()` on its                   │
│ `InstructionsState`. However, because this `TreeEntry` was never fully integrated into the │
│ tree (it has no valid user), its `InstructionsState` was never initialized, leading to the │
│ assertion failure.                                                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to ensure that `getEntryCost` does not process `TreeEntry` nodes that are not   │
│ properly connected to the vectorization tree. A simple and effective way to check for this │
│ is to verify that the `UserTreeIndex` is valid before proceeding with the cost             │
│ calculation.                                                                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s) ###                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to add a check in `BoUpSLP::getEntryCost` to skip `TreeEntry` nodes that have   │
│ an invalid `UserTreeIndex`.                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ // In function: llvm::slpvectorizer::BoUpSLP::getEntryCost                                 │
│ // Add a check at the beginning of the function.                                           │
│                                                                                            │
│ 13318,13318 // llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                             │
│ InstructionCost BoUpSLP::getEntryCost(const TreeEntry *E,                                  │
│                                       ArrayRef<Value *> VectorizedOperands,                │
│                                       SmallPtrSetImpl<Value *> &VectorizedVals) {          │
│   // If the entry is not used by another entry in the tree, it is not going to             │
│   // be vectorized.                                                                        │
│   if (!E->UserTreeIndex.isValid())                                                         │
│     return InstructionCost::getInvalid();                                                  │
│                                                                                            │
│   // We have computed the cost of this node already.                                       │
│   if (E->Cost != InstructionCost::getInvalid()) {                                          │
│     return E->Cost;                                                                        │
│   }                                                                                        │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 5. Conclusion ###                                                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ The crash was caused by the SLP vectorizer attempting to calculate the vectorization cost  │
│ of a `TreeEntry` that was not correctly linked into the dependency graph of the            │
│ vectorization plan. This "dangling" entry had an uninitialized state, which caused an      │
│ assertion to fail when its properties were accessed.                                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ By adding a check at the beginning of `getEntryCost` to ignore entries with an invalid     │
│ `UserTreeIndex`, we ensure that the cost analysis phase only considers nodes that are part │
│ of the actual vectorization tree. This prevents the crash and allows the vectorizer to     │
│ correctly decide that this particular reduction is not profitable to vectorize, proceeding │
│ without error.                                                                             │
