│ "### 1. Understanding the Issue ###\n\nThe `slp-vectorizer` is crashing with an assertion  │
│ failure, `Assertion valid() && \"InstructionsState is invalid.\"' failed`, within the      │
│ `InstructionsState::getMainOp()` method. This indicates that `getMainOp()` is being called │
│ on an `InstructionsState` object that has not been properly initialized.\n\nThe backtrace  │
│ reveals the crash occurs during the cost analysis of a potential vectorization candidate,  │
│ specifically when checking for a \"gather-shuffled\" pattern (`isGatherShuffledEntry`).    │
│ This check involves inspecting a `TreeEntry` that represents a group of scalar             │
│ instructions. The `TreeEntry` contains an `InstructionsState` member (`S`), which holds    │
│ information about the instructions, including the \"main\" operation. The assertion fails  │
│ because this `InstructionsState` is invalid when `getMainOp()` is called on it.\n\n### 2.  │
│ Analyzing `opt`'s Log ###\n\nThe `opt` log provides crucial clues:\n- The vectorizer       │
│ identifies a horizontal reduction involving a chain of `xor` operations.\n- It starts      │
│ building a \"vectorization tree\" and creates several `TreeEntry` nodes.\n- The log shows  │
│ the creation of three `TreeEntry` nodes for `load` instructions.\n- The third `TreeEntry`  │
│ created, for scalars `%7` and `%3`, is printed with `UserTreeIndex: <invalid>`.\n-         │
│ Immediately after, the log shows `SLP: Calculating cost for tree of size 4`, and then the  │
│ crash occurs.\n\nThe invalid `UserTreeIndex` for the third `TreeEntry` is a strong         │
│ indicator of the problem. A `TreeEntry` represents a node in the vectorization tree. Its   │
│ `UserTreeIndex` should point to the `TreeEntry` that uses its result. An invalid index     │
│ suggests this node is disconnected from the main tree structure being built.\n\n### 3.     │
│ Root Cause Analysis ###\n\nThe core issue lies in how `BoUpSLP::buildTree` constructs the  │
│ vectorization tree. When it encounters a set of scalar values, it creates a `TreeEntry`    │
│ for them. If these scalars are operands to another instruction that is also being          │
│ vectorized, the new `TreeEntry`'s `UserTreeIndex` is set to point to the user              │
│ `TreeEntry`.\n\nIn this specific case, the horizontal reduction logic                      │
│ (`HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce`) initiates tree construction. It gathers all the       │
│ operands of the reduction chain (`%0`, `%1`, ..., `%7`). It then calls                     │
│ `BoUpSLP::buildTree` on these operands.\n\nThe problem is that `buildTree` does not create │
│ a root `TreeEntry` for the initial set of scalars passed to it. Instead, it iterates       │
│ through them, finds their users, and builds sub-trees for those. If some of the initial    │
│ scalars are not used by any common instruction that can be vectorized (i.e., they don't    │
│ form a sub-problem that `buildTree` can handle), the `TreeEntry` created for them will not │
│ have a user within the tree being constructed. Consequently, its `UserTreeIndex` remains   │
│ in its default invalid state.\n\nLater, during cost analysis (`getTreeCost`), the          │
│ vectorizer iterates through all `TreeEntry` nodes, including the disconnected one. When    │
│ `getEntryCost` is called on this node, it proceeds down a path that eventually calls       │
│ `getMainOp()` on its `InstructionsState`. However, because this `TreeEntry` was never      │
│ fully integrated into the tree (it has no valid user), its `InstructionsState` was never   │
│ initialized, leading to the assertion failure.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s) ###\n\nThe │
│ fix is to add a check in `BoUpSLP::getEntryCost` to skip `TreeEntry` nodes that have an    │
│ invalid `UserTreeIndex`. I will replace the initial block of the function with a new one   │
│ that includes this check, along with the existing cost-caching check which was missing     │
│ from this location but is good practice to have early.\n\n```cpp\n// File:                 │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n// Replace lines 13348-13352 with the     │
│ following:\n\n  // If the entry is not used by another entry in the tree, it is not going  │
│ to\n  // be vectorized.\n  if (!E->UserTreeIndex.isValid())\n    return                    │
│ InstructionCost::getInvalid();\n\n  // We have computed the cost of this node already.\n   │
│ if (E->Cost != InstructionCost::getInvalid()) {\n    return E->Cost;\n  }\n\n              │
│ ArrayRef<Value *> VL = E->Scalars;\n\n  Type *ScalarTy = getValueType(VL[0]);\n  if        │
│ (!isValidElementType(ScalarTy))\n    return InstructionCost::getInvalid();\n```\n\n### 5.  │
│ Conclusion ###\n\nThe crash was caused by the SLP vectorizer attempting to calculate the   │
│ vectorization cost of a `TreeEntry` that was not correctly linked into the dependency      │
│ graph of the vectorization plan. This \"dangling\" entry had an uninitialized state, which │
│ caused an assertion to fail when its properties were accessed.\n\nBy adding a check at the │
│ beginning of `getEntryCost` to ignore entries with an invalid `UserTreeIndex`, we ensure   │
│ that the cost analysis phase only considers nodes that are part of the actual              │
│ vectorization tree. This prevents the crash and allows the vectorizer to correctly decide  │
│ that this particular reduction is not profitable to vectorize, proceeding without          │
│ error."})                                                                                  │
